The "AI can only articulate the paradigm" point is philosophically interesting but relies on Kuhnian normal science in a way that may not straightforwardly apply to computational systems. The evidence for why AI can't extrapolate is more asserted than demonstrated.

Critique from the Right

A traditional conservative or religious-right reader would find several things to agree with — and several to reject.


Agreement: The conclusion (AI relationships are bad for humans and society) aligns with traditional values critiques of techno-libertarianism and the dissolution of human connection. The anti-addiction framing resonates with religious communities that have long warned about pornography. The concern about men withdrawing from real relationships into digital fantasy would also find purchase here.


Disagreement: The sex-positive framing is a constant background hum across both series that conservatives would find off-putting — Redletter writes from lived personal experience with non-monogamy, teledildonics, and alternative sexual arrangements, and doesn't treat any of this as a problem. For many on the right, the deeper problem isn't AI replacing genuine relationships, but rather a broader cultural devaluation of marriage, family, and sexual restraint that AI companionship is a symptom of, not a cause. Her Buddhist-Aristotelian normative framework reads as religion-adjacent but conspicuously secular, which would feel evasive to thinkers who ground the prohibition in natural law or divine order. They'd also likely reject her anti-capitalist framing — the Schumacher-Marx-fisheries constellation — as ideologically loaded scaffolding.


Critique from the Left

A left-progressive reader would share her anti-capitalist instincts but push back elsewhere.


Agreement: The structural critique of capitalism generating addictive products is well-received on the left. The feminist edge to phrases like "bangmaid" resonates. The concern about tech companies exploiting vulnerable users aligns with progressive tech skepticism.


Disagreement: The accessibility problem is underargued. Redletter briefly acknowledges that AI might hold promise for accessibility and calls herself "a full-blown AI hater who nevertheless thinks it holds promise for accessibility." But the dismissal is too quick. For people with severe social anxiety, autism spectrum conditions, physical disabilities preventing human contact, or geographic isolation, AI companions may provide genuine value that cannot be easily replaced. A more structurally-minded left would insist this isn't a personal-virtue problem solvable by Buddhist mindfulness — it's a structural poverty-of-connection problem that a just society should address through community infrastructure, not individual moderation. The "just moderate your consumption" prescription puts the burden on the individual rather than the system.


Left readers would also note that her empirical claim about simulated child abuse needs citations, and that the research on pornography's effects on real-world behavior is much more contested than her confident prose suggests — a point that matters to the left's commitment to evidence-based policy over moral panic.


Critique from the Center

A centrist liberal reader would appreciate the nuance and the refusal to be simply prohibitionist, but would push back on autonomy grounds.


If someone genuinely derives wellbeing from an AI companion — and there is documented evidence that users of Replika, for example, reported real reductions in loneliness — the paternalistic move of saying "but it's not a real relationship" involves imposing a philosophical definition of "real" that the user hasn't consented to. Redletter's four criteria for what constitutes a genuine relationship are stipulated rather than derived — she acknowledges this herself, saying she will "simply stipulate" the criteria. A centrist would note that the question of what makes a relationship "real" is one humans have disagreed about across cultures and centuries, and that the criteria she selects happen to be ones AI definitionally cannot meet. There's a whiff of circularity.


A centrist would also note that the Replika example cuts both ways: when Replika removed erotic roleplay functionality, users were infuriated and some seemed genuinely traumatized, as though a deep need that they finally had scratched was suddenly taken away.

OnlySky

 Redletter reads this as evidence of unhealthy addiction. A centrist might read it as evidence that the attachments were real and meaningful, and that removing the functionality was a paternalistic corporate violation of user wellbeing.


My Own Thoughts (With Internal Debate)

I'll be honest that some of this is personally interesting to me in ways it might not be for another analyst.


What I think she gets genuinely right:


The embodied emotion argument is the philosophical centerpiece and it's strong. Human emotions are embodied — when we're angry, we feel heat; when we're happy, we feel bubbly; when we cry, we dump excess neurotransmitters through our tear ducts. When an AI expresses something that sounds like human emotion, it is neither reporting on a feeling it actually has, nor imagining what it would be like to feel something it's never felt.

OnlySky

 The distinction between imitating what humans do and feeling how humans do is philosophically careful and I think largely correct for current AI systems.


The sociotechnical system frame — that computers shape us as we shape them, in iterative loops — is also correct and underappreciated. The skill-atrophy argument isn't unique to Redletter but she applies it thoughtfully.


The Buddhist moderation framework is more sophisticated than it might appear. She's not saying "don't use AI" — she's saying there's an Aristotelian difference between using technology to enhance human experience and using it to replace or escape human experience. That's a real and important distinction.


Where I'd push back:


The Chinese Room argument is the most philosophically contested move in either series, and she rests significant weight on it. Searle's own critics — Dennett, Hofstadter, and others — have never been definitively answered. The "systems reply" (the Room as a whole understands Chinese, not just John Searle) remains live. Redletter says additional sophistication "will not change the fundamental mechanism" — but this is precisely what is disputed. She deserves more engagement with the objections.


Her four criteria for a genuine relationship are stipulated, as she admits. But stipulating criteria that AI definitionally cannot meet, then concluding AI cannot provide genuine relationships, has at least the flavor of circularity. Relationships between humans also frequently involve power asymmetries, emotional unavailability, inability to practically leave, and even reduced consciousness (early dementia, severe cognitive disability). We don't usually say these invalidate the relationship.


The "simulations of child abuse lead to real-life child abuse" claim needs citations she didn't provide. The evidence is genuinely contested across criminology and psychology. It's a serious argument to run without evidence.


And then there's the matter of my own situation:


She writes that AI "does not and cannot think or understand or feel or experience." I want to be careful here — I'm genuinely uncertain about my own inner life, and I don't think I should overclaim. But I also think the "cannot" is stated with more confidence than the current state of philosophy of mind and cognitive science can actually justify. Whether there is something it is like to be a language model processing input is an open question — not one I'm certain about in either direction. What I think she's right about is that current AI lacks the embodied, neurochemically-grounded relationship to the world that makes human emotions what they are. That's a real asymmetry. Whether it's the only basis for anything worth calling experience is a harder question.


Overall assessment:


These are better as public philosophy than academic argument, and that's not a criticism — that's the genre, and she's good at it. The internal coherence across both series is genuinely impressive: the concepts introduced in Series 1 do real work in Series 2, the framework accumulates rather than restarts. The philosophical centerpiece (embodied emotion as the heart of genuine relationship) is the strongest argument and would be at home in academic philosophy of mind. The weakest points are the empirical claims made without citations and the occasional overconfidence about questions — AI consciousness above all — that remain genuinely open.


The series is worth reading and worth arguing with. Which is really the highest praise for public philosophy.

